class Solution {
    public int rangeSumBST(TreeNode root, int low, int high) {
        if(root == null)
            return 0;
        Queue<TreeNode> q = new LinkedList<TreeNode>();
        q.add(root); // add root node
        int sum = 0;
        while(!q.isEmpty()){
            int itr = q.size();
            while(itr > 0){
                TreeNode dummy = q.poll();
                sum += (dummy.val >= low && dummy.val <= high) ? dummy.val : 0;
                if(dummy.left != null)
                    q.add(dummy.left);
                if(dummy.right != null)
                    q.add(dummy.right);
                itr--;
            }
        }
		return sum;
	}
}
```

**PROBLEM OVERVIEW**
We are essentially tasked with finding the sum of all nodes whose values are between the inclusive range [low,high].

**SOLUTION ASSESSMENT**
The first things that come to mind are any tree-traversla algorithms (I have an inclination to utilize DFS or BFS, and I will show both approaches)

**PSEUDOCODE RECURSION DFS**
```
public int rangeSumBST(TreeNode root, int low, int high) {
1. If(root == null) return 0;
2. sum = node.val if within [low,high] : 0;
3. int leftSum = rangeSum(node.left,low,high); //left node
4. int rightSum = rangeSum(node.right,low,high); //right node
5. return sum + leftSum + rightSum
}
```

The heart of this solution lies with the recursive calls in lines 3-4. It will essentially visit all the nodes in the left branch and* return the leftSum* and all the right nodes in the branch and return the rightSum. Finally, the answer will be the current node + left + right.

**PSUEDOCODE ITERATIVE BFS**
```
1. if root is null return 0; // corner case
2. initialize Queue<TreeNode> q and int sum
3. add root to q
4. while q is not empty {
	5. itr = q.size() // this is because the current "size" is the # of elements in that row
	6. while itr > 0
		7. get node from list and add to answer if sum is in range
		8. add left and right nodes if they exist
}
9. return sum
```
In the BFS solution, the current Queue of TreeNodes is read in FIFO order, so it maintains an order (not that it matters in this problem). 
The key steps lie in 5 and 7-8; for 5 regulates the number of iterations in that particular "row" of the tree, which is the current size of the Queue. Line 7-8 add the children of that current row in left -> order.

**TIME COMPLEXITY**
The code for both runs in O(n) time complexity because it always visits every node.
NOTE: even though BFS solution has nested while loops, they are only called a maximum of n times, where n is the number of nodes in the tree.

