1. Naive approach 

Traverse the entire tree, note the nodes that falls under the range, and add them all together. This is the simplest possible solution with O(N) time complexity and O(N) memory.

```
func rangeSumBST(root *TreeNode, low int, high int) int {
        if root == nil {
                return 0
        }
        var sum = 0
        if root.Val >= low && root.Val <= high {
                sum += root.Val
        }

        l := rangeSumBST(root.Left, low, high)

        r := rangeSumBST(root.Right, low, high)
        return sum + l + r
}
```

2. Optimal Solution

Now, can we do better? **YES**.  There are plenty of **unneccesary** work in the previous solution. 

Remember, it's a **Binary Search Tree**, meaning, the left node is guaranteed to have a smaller value than the root, and the right node is guaranteed to have a greater value than the root. 

Why would we want to traverse the **LEFT** subtree if the **low >= root.Val**, similarly, why would we want to traverse the **RIGHT** subtree if **high <= root.Val**?

With these optimizations our avg. time complexity becomes O(logN) on average.

```
func rangeSumBST(root *TreeNode, low int, high int) int {
        if root == nil {
                return 0
        }

        var sum = 0

        if root.Val >= low && root.Val <= high {
                sum += root.Val
        }

        l := 0
        r := 0

        if low <= root.Val {
                l = rangeSumBST(root.Left, low, high)
        }

        if high >= root.Val {
                r = rangeSumBST(root.Right, low, high)
        }

        return sum + l + r
}
```

