# Intuition
Traverse the entire tree, but add only those nodes whose values fall within the range.

# Approach
Declare a global variable 'sum' to store the range sum.
Traverse the tree using DFS.
In each recursion, check if the node value is in between high and low. If so, add node value to 'sum'.
Return 'sum'.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n) - where n is the total number of nodes in the tree

- Space complexity:
Average case - log(n) [stack space used by recursive calls]
Worst case - O(n) if the tree is completely skewed.

# Code
```
/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * public class TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode left;
 *     TreeNode right;
 *     TreeNode() {}
 *     TreeNode(int val) { this.val = val; }
 *     TreeNode(int val, TreeNode left, TreeNode right) {
 *         this.val = val;
 *         this.left = left;
 *         this.right = right;
 *     }
 * }
 */
class Solution {
    int sum;
    public int rangeSumBST(TreeNode root, int low, int high) {
        sum = 0;
        traverse(root, low, high);
        return sum;
    }

    void traverse(TreeNode node, int low, int high){
        if(node == null){
            return;
        }
        if(node.val >= low && node.val <= high){
            sum += node.val;
        }

        traverse(node.left, low, high);
        traverse(node.right, low, high);
    }
}
```

